quotedObject.fullText:
Honestly this is actually a great question.

You don't want to plug your grounding mat ever into an outlet for a few reasons.

1) Depending on where you live, your earthing wires can be linked to neutral wires at many places - switchboards, power poles, transformers within the network etc.

Neutral wires can draw current and back feed from any part of the system and may pass through your grounding mat. You don't want any artificial current (amps) running through you whatsoever. 

When I used to work in the powerline industry we would always get 1-3 amps running through a neutral that is feeding power to a house.

2) Due to this, the magnetic field of the AC grid (dirty electricity/DE) will still be present somewhat but I am unsure as to the level of significance and frequency (Hz) of it. It would be a lower intensity. But still feel like it would be detrimental because you're plugging directly into it nevertheless.

You can install your own earth rod (https://t.co/DEhakmj9iK) using a hammer (make sure there's no pipes, etc. where you are installing it), and connect a copper wire there with some form of connectors (https://t.co/a2iUpQOSnJ). That would be the best option as you are isolated from everything.

You can literally make your own grounding mats / sheets too just get some thin copper sheets off amazon, and they may have a place to clamp on with some copper wire (https://t.co/pNF2mE5VOD). Run that copper wire to and from the earth stake, and boom. Grounding mat / sheet for under $50.
